\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b n}) Subsp. {\b praepropera.} (A. Kerner) Bornm.,{\i  Bot. Jahrb. }{\b 59}: 483 (1925) ({\i A. praepropera} (A. Kerner) G. Beck, {\i A. spruneri} (Boiss.) G. Beck, {\i A. dillenii} auct. mult., non Schultes ex G. Don fil., nec sensu Rothm.): Stems 10-35 cm, ascending to erect, hirsute below. Lowest leaves usually with only 1 leaflet; uppermost leaves equifoliolate with 7-13 leaflets. Calyx purple at apex; corolla red to purplish.{\i  Mediterranean region, but absent from Spain and much of Italy.} Al Bl Co Cr Ga Gr It Ju Sa Tu.
\par

\pard\f0\fs28  Occasional robust variants approach subsp. ({\b p}).
\par

\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b o}) Subsp. {\b weldeniana.} (Reichenb.) Cullen,{\i  Watsonia }{\b 6}: 389 (1968) ({\i A. weldeniana} Reichenb.): Like subsp. ({\b n}) but lowest leaves with 5-9 broadly elliptical leaflets.{\i  Italy, N. & W. Jugoslavia.} It Ju.
\par

\pard\f0\fs28  Intermediates to subsp. ({\b n}) are common in the coastal part of Jugoslavia. For intermediates to subsp. ({\b s}) see that subspecies. Intermediates to subsp. ({\b c}) ({\i A. tricolor} Vuk.) occur inland in N. Jugoslavia.
\par

\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b p}) Subsp. {\b maura} (G. Beck) Lindb., {\i Acta Soc. Sci. Fenn.} nov. ser., B, {\b 1}({\b 2}): 77 (1932) ({\i A. maura} G. Beck): Stems 30-60 cm, hirsute below; lowest leaves with 1-3 leaflets, the terminal leaflet often very large (5-10 cm); uppermost leaves equifoliolate with 9-13 leaflets. Calyx red at apex; corolla usually red.{\i  W. & S. Portugal, S. & E. Spain, S. Italy, Sicilia.} Hs It Lu Si. ({\i N. Africa.})
\par

\pard\f0\fs28  Variants from Spain (except the extreme south) differ from the typical plant in being less robust, and with the leaves not so evenly distributed along the stem; they appear to be intermediate to either subsp. ({\b n}) or subsp. ({\b i}), and have been given a variety of names, the most common being {\i A. gandogeri} Sagorski and {\i A. font-queri} Rothm. Very fleshy-leaved plants ({\i A. pachyphylla} Rothm.) occur in coastal regions of C. Portugal. They are apparently an ecological modification.
\par

\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b q}) Subsp. {\b hispidissima} (Sagorski) Cullen,{\i  Watsonia}{\b  6}: 389 (1968) ({\i A. hispidissima }Sagorski): Stems 20-25 cm, ascending, hirsute over their whole length; lowermost leaves with 1-3 leaflets; uppermost leaves equifoliolate with 9-11 leaflets. Calyx concolorous; corolla yellow when dry.{\i  Macedonia. }Gr Ju. ({\i Anatolia.})
\par

\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b r}) Subsp. {\b corbierei} (Salmon & Travis) Cullen, {\i Watsonia.}{\b  6}: 295 (1967) ({\i A. maritima} var. {\i corbierei }Salmon & Travis): Like subsp. ({\b q}) but the leaves fleshy; indumentum of the whole plant less dense. •{\i  W. Britain} ({\i Anglesey, Cornwall});{\i  Channel Islands} ({\i Sark}). Br Ga.
